{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"111c3949-5019-4ca8-8478-0b169b38eee1","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_6VG9HaHqogkPeJn8gX3TvD","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Investigating MAUI Java issue"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_8O41sdRM608s4YuKPHucdS","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-d9a5a8ef92bc4653a8cb4282fe696c5c"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-d9a5a8ef92bc4653a8cb4282fe696c5c."}],"interactionId":"e7af4396-b3a4-4f6a-a563-53d9f9bffaac","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nLet me think about common .NET MAUI Android + Java issues:\n\n1. .NET MAUI / Xamarin Android builds require a specific JDK version. Starting with .NET 8, the Android SDK requires JDK 17. But there can be issues with the specific JDK distribution or version.\n\n2. A very common issue on macOS is that JAVA_HOME needs to point to the correct path. On macOS with Adoptium Temurin, the path is typically `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`.\n\n\n3. .NET MAUI bundles its own JDK (Microsoft OpenJDK) and may bypass the system JAVA_HOME entirely—the build process actually uses the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property to determine which JDK to use. The .NET 8+ Android workload ships with Microsoft's OpenJDK 17, so using a different JDK distribution like Adoptium can sometimes cause compatibility issues with the Android build tools or the build tooling may look for JDK in a specific location that differs from where Adoptium is installed.\n\n4. On macOS specifically, the Android build can fail if the JDK vendor isn't recognized or if there's a version mismatch with what the Android Gradle plugin expects. The real issue is that .NET MAUI Android builds rely on the JDK configured through Android SDK settings rather than JAVA_HOME—if `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` isn't set correctly or there's a mismatch between what the build system expects and what's actually installed, the build fails. The user is likely running into this exact scenario. The build might be picking up the wrong JDK, or there could be a conflict between Temurin and the Microsoft OpenJDK that .NET 8+ MAUI installs automatically. The real issue is likely that different build tools are using different JDK versions, causing a mismatch. Let me reconsider what the actual error might be—.NET 8+ should handle JDK configuration automatically, so the problem could be something more specific about how JAVA_HOME is set up on macOS.\n\nLooking at common Java errors in MAUI Android builds, it's probably either a version mismatch error, a missing JDK, or an environment variable issue. The most likely culprit is that .NET 8/9 MAUI requires JDK 17 and expects the Microsoft OpenJDK by default, so if that's not installed or if JAVA_HOME points elsewhere, the build fails. The solution would be to either install the Microsoft OpenJDK 17 that comes with the MAUI workload or adjust the environment configuration. is that the Microsoft OpenJDK isn't installed, or the Temurin path isn't being recognized correctly. On macOS, Temurin 17 typically lives at `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`, and JAVA_HOME needs to point to that exact location including the `/Contents/Home` suffix.\n\nThere's also a possibility that JDK 17.0.12 specifically has compatibility issues with the Android build tools—I'm recalling some problems with newer 17 patch releases where changes to `java.lang.module` broke the D8/R8 dexer that Android uses.\n\nThe most likely culprit on macOS though is the JAVA_HOME path format—it needs to include `/Contents/Home` at the end for the build system to find it correctly. Though given that the user verified `java -version` works, they might already have this set up properly.\n\nLet me focus on the most probable diagnosis: the .NET Android/MAUI build system has specific requirements that might not be met by the current setup. someone has Temurin 17.0.12 on macOS and MAUI Android build fails with Java errors. The core issue is that .NET MAUI's Android toolchain specifically expects the Microsoft build of OpenJDK 17, and it may not properly detect or use Temurin even if it's installed. The fix is either to use the bundled Microsoft OpenJDK that comes with the MAUI workload, or to explicitly point the build to Temurin by setting the `JavaSdkDirectory` property. I'm recalling there's a specific macOS issue related to how JDK installations are discovered when installed via Homebrew or Adoptium's installer—\n\nthe standard approach of setting `JAVA_HOME` doesn't actually work with MAUI's build system since it uses its own detection logic. Starting with .NET 8, the Android workload bundles Microsoft OpenJDK 17, and the build checks the `JavaSdkDirectory` property first, then the bundled JDK, and only falls back to `JAVA_HOME` as a last resort. If the bundled JDK is corrupted or partially installed, the build fails even though a working Temurin JDK is available through `JAVA_HOME`. The most practical solution is to either repair the bundled JDK or explicitly configure the build to use Temurin.\n\nLet me check if there are any relevant plugins or configurations in the repository that might provide additional context for this issue.","outputTokens":2906,"requestId":"942B:840A1:13F6398:1661FF5:6A067081"},"id":"e686fa09-13ed-4e10-b025-9c82de7f5dc5","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:02:48.950Z","parentId":"b2c1b1cd-9b8a-4388-97f0-2b73bd3701fd"}
